On the 1980s and the 1990s, was the 1980s a new golden age in bookselling and book collecting?
As David Redden has asserted, and as Ed Wolff said, he said, well, I didn't see any picklet papers, not picklet papers, Paul Richard Alman, actually.
You know, a golden age.
He said, we'd love to have a complete set of books.
I guess what he's saying is that there's some wonderful things available, but you still couldn't, by the way, Huntington was able to buy 70, 80 years ago.
But nevertheless, there were some marvelous things because of the changes in the tax laws and the institutions.
Not getting the material that they want.
That's a very dry, unfocused state.
But maybe if you could just give me a comment on the 80s and what you see in the 90s.
How's that?
My view of the thought of high prices and big time auctions really starts in November 1985.
It's the first time we had a general miscellaneous consigned sale.
from various owners that was 100% sold across the board.
There seemed at that time to be a situation where everything just sold at Auckland.
Everything sold and for very high prices.
There had been great sales with us before.
Some of our greatest sales, namely
the Chew Sale in 1982, in which we had the original manuscript of the Mason-Dixon line, and the Declaration of Independence, and the Charter for Pennsylvania.
A sale like that made $800,000.
A sale like that today would bring $5 million.
Even today?
I'm saying today, from 82 to 91, it would bring $5 million.
Today, well, assuming that a copy of the Declaration of Independence belonging to Justice Chew with an impeccable provenance, it's got to bring as much as the last one, mate, I would have thought.
Which nobody knows what to know.

You want me to guess?

before being sold in 1969.

and it was shown to Freddie Goff, he showed it to me, and we sold it a year after the two, the two copy.

any more than, I mean, one knows that among these dealers, in the old days, a dealer would have a cast-iron relationship with certain collectors or librarians.
